Overview

The goal of this lab is to introduce the basics of shiny, a package used to build apps in RStudio. shiny allows users to build interactive graphics to explore and tell stories with their data. Students should begin by exploring the shiny website there are a lot of great resources and examples to explore.

This labs main objective will be to re-reinforce and slightly extend the shiny basics covered in lesson 1 and lesson 2.

We slightly extend the material by incorporating ggplot graphics instead of the base R graphics that they use in their examples.

Dataset

To complete this lab we require the familiar cdc.txt dataset. As a reminder the dataset variables are

  • genhlth - How would you rate your general health? (excellent, very good, good, fair, poor)
  • exerany - Have you exercised in the past month? (1=yes, 0=no)
  • hlthplan - Do you have some form of health coverage? (1=yes, 0=no)
  • smoke100 - Have you smoked at least 100 cigarettes in your life time? (1=yes, 0=no)
  • height - height in inches
  • weight - weight in pounds
  • wtdesire - weight desired in pounds
  • age - in years
  • gender - m for male and f for female


Submission Guidelines

You will be submitting a zip file that contains all app directories (each app gets a directory/file). The zip file should follow our standard naming convention: Kuyper_Arend_L11.zip.

  1. Create a directory/file using the standard naming convention: Kuyper_Arend_L11.
  2. Each app should have its own subdirectory/file in the Kuyper_Arend_L11 directory/file as pictured. Note that each app directory/file should have an app.R script.

  1. Compress/zip the Kuyper_Arend_L11 directory/file to get the Kuyper_Arend_L11.zip file as pictured.

  1. Submit the Kuyper_Arend_L11.zip file on Canvas.


Exercises

Complete the following exercises.


Exercise 1

Work through lesson 1 and lesson 2 which both contain an exercise for practice. In the case of lesson 1s exercise you should have replaced the base R graphics code with ggplot code (i.e.make the histogram using ggplot2). Submit your shiny applications for lessons 1 and 2.


Exercise 2

Using your app.R for exercise 1 for lesson 1s exercise and the cdc.txt dataset, create the shiny app pictured below. For a closer look you can access the shiny app at https://amkuyper.shinyapps.io/CDCapp/.


Exercise 3

This task focuses on building a user-interface much like lesson 2. Using your home state or one that you would like to visit, construct a shiny app that is similar to the one pictured below. The idea is to explore the shiny options for text, images, and HTML tags discussed in lesson 2 (shiny HTML Tags Glossary). Feel free to to be as creative with the options as you want.
